'''Patrick Berg''' (born 24 November 1997) is a Norwegian professional [[association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[defensive midfielder]] for [[Eliteserien]] club [[FK Bodø/Glimt|Bodø/Glimt]] and the [[Norway national football team|Norway national team]].

== Club career ==

===Bodø/Glimt===
Berg was born in [[Bodø (town)|Bodø]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.altomfotball.no/element.do?cmd=player&personId=286256&tournamentId=1&seasonId=336&teamId=307&useFullUrl=false |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140915034632/http://www.altomfotball.no/element.do?cmd=player&personId=286256&tournamentId=1&seasonId=336&teamId=307&useFullUrl=false |url-status=dead |archive-date=15 September 2014 |title=Patrick Berg |work=altomfotball.no |publisher=TV2 |accessdate=17 September 2014}}</ref> He made his senior debut for [[FK Bodø/Glimt|Bodø/Glimt]] on 12 July 2014 in a 3–0 loss to [[Odds BK|Odd]].{{Citation needed|date=January 2022}}

===Lens===
On 20 December 2021, Berg signed for [[Ligue 1]] side [[RC Lens|Lens]] on a contract until 2026. The transfer fee paid to Bodø/Glimt was reportedly €4.5 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lequipe.fr/Football/Actualites/Patrick-berg-signe-a-lens-jusqu-en-2026-officiel/1306402 |title=Patrick Berg signe à Lens jusqu'en 2026 (officiel) |language=French |publisher=lequipe.fr |accessdate=20 December 2021 |date=20 December 2021}}</ref>

===Return to Bodø/Glimt===
On 29 August 2022, after only six months in [[France]], Berg decided to return to Norway and rejoin his boyhood club, [[FK Bodø/Glimt|Bodø/Glimt]].<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Bodø/Glimt|url=https://www.glimt.no/nyheter/patrick-berg-kommer-hjem--mer-motivert-enn-noen-gang|title=Patrick Berg Kommer Hjen: – Mer Motivert Enn Noen Gang|date=29 August 2022|access-date=29 August 2022|language=no}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|date=29 August 2022 |lang=fr |title=Patrick Berg (Lens) rentre en Norvège et retourne à Bodo Glimt |url=https://www.lequipe.fr/Football/Actualites/Patrick-berg-lens-rentre-en-norvege-et-retourne-a-bodo-glimt/1350811 |website=www.lequipe.fr}}<!-- auto-translated from French by Module:CS1 translator --></ref>
On 3 September 2023, Berg scored twice in a league match against [[Hamarkameratene]]. Despite his brace, neither side was able to secure victory, with the match ending in a 4–4 draw.

Berg won the [[Eliteserien|Norwegian league title]] for a third time as Bodø/Glimt were once again crowned champions at the end of the [[2023 Eliteserien|2023 season]].<ref>{{cite web|date=12 November 2023 |lang=no |title=BodøØ/Glimt Er Seriemestere: − Har Blitt en Fotballstormakt |url=https://www.vg.no/sport/fotball/i/5B750b/bodoe-glimt-er-seriemestere-har-blitt-en-fotball-stormakt |website=www.vg.no}}<!-- auto-translated from French by Module:CS1 translator --></ref>

==International career==
In August 2020, Berg received his first call-up to the [[Norway national football team|Norway national team]] for [[2020–21 UEFA Nations League|UEFA Nations League]] matches against [[Austria national football team|Austria]] and [[Northern Ireland national football team|Northern Ireland]].<ref>{{cite web|date=24 August 2020 |lang=no |title=Her er Norges tropp mot Østerrike og Nord-Irland |url=https://www.fotball.no/landslag/norge-a-herrer/2020/her-er-norges-tropp-mot-osterrike-og-nord-irland/ |website=www.fotball.no}}<!-- auto-translated from French by Module:CS1 translator --></ref> However, he remained an unused substitute in both matches. He was called up again in November 2020, but after testing positive for [[COVID-19]] despite being asymptomatic, he was placed in quarantine and was ultimately unable to make his senior international debut during that international break.<ref>{{cite web|date=20 November 2020 |title=Trois nouveaux internationaux norvégiens positifs au coronavirus |url=https://www.lequipe.fr/Football/Actualites/Trois-nouveaux-internationaux-norvegiens-positifs-au-coronavirus/1196456 |website=lequipe.fr}}<!-- auto-translated from French by Module:CS1 translator --></ref>

On 24 March 2021, Berg made his international debut for the Norway national team in a [[2022 FIFA World Cup qualification (UEFA)|World Cup qualifier]] against [[Gibraltar national football team|Gibraltar]], making him Norway's first ever third-generation international footballer.{{Citation needed|date=December 2021}}

On 21 May 2026, Berg was included in the 26-man squad selected by Norway national team manager [[Ståle Solbakken]] for the [[2026 FIFA World Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|access-date=1 June 2026 |date=21 May 2026 |language=en |title=Norway squad announcement |url=https://www.fifa.com/en/tournaments/mens/worldcup/canadamexicousa2026/articles/norway-squad-announcement-stale-solbakken |website=[[FIFA]]}}<!-- auto-translated from French by Module:CS1 translator --></ref>

==Personal life==
Berg comes from a football family; his father [[Ørjan Berg]], his grandfather [[Harald Berg]], his uncles [[Arild Berg|Arild]] and [[Runar Berg]], and his great uncle Knut Berg have all played for Bodø/Glimt. Harald, Ørjan, and Runar have also played for the [[Norway national football team|national team]].

